# Using ofstream ✍️

It works exactly like `cout`!

```cpp
#include <fstream>
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ofstream MyFile("test.txt");

    if (MyFile.is_open()) {
        MyFile << "Hello C++ Files!";
        MyFile << "\nThis is easy.";
        MyFile.close();
    }
}
```
`close()` is essential to flush the buffer and free resources.

# Using ifstream 📖

It works like `cin`, but we usually use `getline` to read full lines.

```cpp
string line;
ifstream MyFile("test.txt");

if (MyFile.is_open()) {
    while (getline(MyFile, line)) {
        cout << line << endl;
    }
    MyFile.close();
}
```

# Safety First ⛑️

Always check if the file opened successfully. It might fail if:
- File doesn't exist (for reading).
- No permission.
- Disk full.

```cpp
if (!file.is_open()) {
    cout << "Error opening file!";
    exit(1);
}
```

